# Enforce LF line endings in the working tree on every platform.
#
# git-your-lark records content hashes (sha256) of local Markdown/asset files
# in `.git-your-lark/state.json` and compares them again during `verify`/
# `pull verify`. On Windows, git's default `core.autocrlf=true` would check
# text files out as CRLF, so the on-disk bytes (and their hash) would differ
# from the LF bytes stored/committed on macOS, producing spurious "remote
# content changed" drift. Pinning `eol=lf` keeps the on-disk content identical
# across macOS, Linux, and Windows and eliminates the hash drift. This is a
# no-op on macOS/Linux, where text files already use LF.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Treat binary assets as binary so git never attempts line-ending conversion
# or diffing on them (matters for the `assets/` images bundled with docs and
# fixtures).
*.png binary
*.jpg binary
*.jpeg binary
*.gif binary
*.webp binary
*.ico binary
